<br>
The vast majority of your time spent raiding is about farming loot to enable you to raid harder mobs.<br>
<br>
When you first attempt a mob, the encounter is challenging.  The equipment that mob drops makes your raid force better.  As you kill that mob over and over again, your raid force gets that much better and better until it is capable of taking on the &quot;next mob up the step&quot;.<br>
<br>
I'd honestly say that 20% of the raids most dedicated raiding guilds do are honestly a challenge.  The balance of the 80% are &quot;trivial&quot; encounters that must be done to farm the gear needed to make the next challenge possible.<br>
<br>
So while it's correct to say that raiding is not all about loot, saying that raiding is not at all about loot is naieve.  Without that loot, you can't progress to the more difficult encounters.<br>
<br>
Why do wizards go on Hate raids?  Because those raids make the raid force as a whole better.  Why do people go on raids if most raids they get no loot?  Again, because on every successful raid, someone does get an upgrade and thus the capabilities of the raiding force increase.  Why do they want to see the capabilities of the raid force increase?  Because they want to do the next challenging thing.<br>
